1.c: obsolescence. Poor housing. Influx of lower class population.
1.b: good transportation, schools, etc. Near shopping center. Close to diversified industrial employment.

areaDesc.5: This area is well located for local labor, but the type of occupant moving in is of lower class and the general trend of the section is downward moderately fast. Little upswing in prices is anticipated. Rentals can not be substantially increased because of incomes.

1.c: poor housing. Heavy obsolescence. Objectionable gas refining fumes.
1.b: good transportation, schools, etc. Near diversified employment.

areaDesc.5: Section south of the railroad is a slum area. Negro is concentrated around the West St. Station. The bulk of the two-family houses are converted singles.

1.c: obsolescence. Low class occupants. Poor housing. Adjacent to dumping grounds of city of Maldea.

areaDesc.5: This neighborhood is a fair 4th grade section which is declining constantly in desirability as lower type buyers come into the section.

1.c: obsolescence. Changing ownership. Infiltration of lower class occupant.
1.b: fairly desirable residential neighborhood of modest houses. Conveniently located with good transportation, schools, churches, etc.

areaDesc.5: Pride of ownership is still apparent throughout the neighborhood, but the general trend of this section is downward as the potential buyers is predominately foreign. A nominal increase in prices may be anticipated but not to approach 1929 prices. Broadway is principally small business with the important square at Ferry intersection.
